  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improved access to emergency nutrition care for severely malnourished children with complications in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The capacity of partners to deliver quality nutrition services continues to be a challenge.Approximately 15% of child cases of Severe Acute Malnutrition develop complications, needing specialised inpatient care through Therapeutic feeding units (TFU&apos;s). Complications such as anorexia, infections or metabolic dysfunction still warrants inpatient management and contribute towards reduction of mortality amongst children with severe acute malnutrition. The Public Nutrition Department-MOPH with support from UNICEF and WHO have observed that the existing TFU&apos;s were were in a poor state and required urgent attention. A significant number of district hospitals in the targeted provinces do not have TFU&#x2019;s and therefore need establishment of new facilities.Extra support for effective management of acute malnutrition is required in areas offering treatment for severe acute malnutrition.The project will strengthen operational and staff&#x2019;s functional capacity in 37 In-patient Department of Severe Acute Malnutrition IPD/SAM) located in 12 priority provinces (30 existing and 7 new sites). Prioritization is according to the Nutrition cluster based on provinces with Severe Acute Malnutrition more than 3%.  The TFU&#x2019;s comprise of 4-CHC+, 21-District Hospitals, 9-Provincial Hospitals, 2-Referral Hospitals, and 1-Referral Hospital (Teaching Hospital). The overall project will involve assessment and rehabilitation of 37targeted TFUs&#x2019; in 12 priority provinces. The targeted TFU&#x2019;s will undergo assessment followed by functional upgrading, through the provision/replacement of and ensure adequate provision of F-75/F-100 milk preparation kits. Equipment including kitchen items, cold chain, warming system, bed side chairs for caretakers and other items, thus ensuring the quality and efficient continuity of services provided by the TFUs. The targeted TFU&#x2019;s will undergo Rehabilitation of water, hygiene, sanitation and environmental health systems, Provision  of a comprehensive basic WASH and environmental health package to ensure that nosocomial transmission of diarrhea ARI and other seasonal infections will be reduced by strengthening Infection Prevention measures. The rehabilitated sites will be monitored for functionality and provision of quality services for children admitted with Severe Acute Malnutrition. Health workers in the targeted TFU&apos;s will receive training on inpatient management of SAM as well as on water, sanitation and hygiene aspects. The activities will therefore contribute towards quality treatment of Severe acute malnutrition (SAM cases), a life threatening condition requiring urgent treatment and therefore contribute towards decreasing the under-five case-fatality rate.</narrative>
  </description>
